I meant the second way. You only want one instance of the custom functions plugin, but it should be able to scan multiple files for functions tagged as @customfunction.

I'm not actively working in this area now, but I know that I wanted to make sure it was possible to have custom functions in more than one source file. There were some changes with webpack, so maybe this was broken. 

You might first try the approach to have just "./src/functions/functions.ts" in the list. Try to create an exported function in in a second file, and then import into functions.ts.

file: functions2.ts

/**
@customfunction
*/ 
export function doSomething()
{
}


file: functions.ts

import { doSomething } from "functions2";

